  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Cannon Hill has quietly become one of the more practical choices in Brisbane's inner east for buyers who want suburban space within striking distance of the city. The suburb sits between Morningside and Murarrie along the Wynnum Road corridor, with Cannon Hill train station offering a direct route into the CBD in under 20 minutes. The housing stock is predominantly post-war, with a mix of original timber homes, brick-and-tile builds from the 1970s and 1980s, and an increasing number of homes that have been substantially renovated or rebuilt entirely.</p>

      <p>The suburb does not have the heritage reputation of Hawthorne or the prestige of Balmoral, and sellers should not expect Balmoral prices. What Cannon Hill does offer is genuine family liveability at a price point that still attracts motivated buyers with borrowing capacity, and that combination produces reasonably competitive sale conditions for well-presented homes. Understanding how to position a Cannon Hill property correctly is the difference between a sale that meets expectations and one that exceeds them.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Cannon Hill</h2>
      <p>The primary buyer in Cannon Hill is a family with young to primary-school-age children. Many are coming from apartments or townhouses in the inner east and are making their first purchase of a detached house. They are focused on land size, the condition of the kitchen and bathrooms, the quality of outdoor space, and access to schools. Cannon Hill State School has a good reputation within the suburb, and proximity to it features in many buyers' search criteria. A secondary buyer segment is the owner-occupier renovator: buyers who are comfortable taking on a project in exchange for a lower entry price and the opportunity to build equity through improvement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Cannon Hill</h2>
      <p>Block size and land shape are the two most important value drivers in Cannon Hill. Homes on 600-plus square metre blocks, particularly those with a north-facing rear or a wide frontage that allows future development, attract the strongest buyer interest across multiple segments simultaneously. A renovator and a family buyer will both inspect the same generous block, which creates competition at campaign level. Streets closer to the train station and Wynnum Road amenity also tend to perform better than those on the eastern edge of the suburb, where access to retail and transport requires more driving.</p>

      <p>Renovation quality matters. A Cannon Hill home that has been competently renovated, with a functional kitchen, updated bathrooms, and a weather-protected outdoor area, will achieve meaningfully more than a comparable home that has been half-renovated or updated cosmetically without addressing the structural elements. Buyers in this price bracket are aware that renovation costs have increased significantly, and they price in the work they will need to do. Remove that discount by completing the work before you sell.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing for sale</h2>
      <p>Cannon Hill buyers conduct thorough pre-purchase due diligence. Pest and building reports are standard, and any issues that emerge will be used to negotiate a price reduction or withdraw from the contract. The best way to protect your outcome is to commission your own pre-sale pest and building inspection, address whatever is material, and be in a position to provide the report on request. It removes the negotiating leverage a buyer might otherwise use and signals that the property has been properly maintained.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Timing and campaign approach</h2>
      <p>Cannon Hill has enough buyer depth to support auction campaigns for quality family homes, particularly in the spring and autumn markets when buyer activity is strongest. Private treaty works well for properties with a more specific buyer profile, such as homes that need significant renovation or properties on smaller blocks with limited development potential. The right approach depends on your specific property and the current state of buyer activity, not on a default preference. A conversation with an agent who knows the suburb's current conditions is the starting point for making the right call.</p>

